00:26:36,296 --> 00:26:37,850
Advance.

269
00:27:06,995 --> 00:27:07,954
Lie down!

270
00:27:10,227 --> 00:27:11,551
Ready...

271
00:27:11,551 --> 00:27:12,625
Stand up!

272
00:27:14,543 --> 00:27:16,106
Advance.

273
00:27:17,909 --> 00:27:19,942
Lie down!

274
00:27:21,621 --> 00:27:23,539
Ready...

275
00:27:23,539 --> 00:27:24,498
Stand up!

276
00:27:26,540 --> 00:27:27,854
Advance.

277
00:27:29,897 --> 00:27:31,451
Lie down!

278
00:27:33,494 --> 00:27:35,057
Ready...

279
00:27:35,651 --> 00:27:36,850
Stand up!

280
00:27:40,207 --> 00:27:41,406
You.

281
00:27:45,606 --> 00:27:47,160
Again.

282
00:27:50,037 --> 00:27:51,360
Again!

283
00:28:04,672 --> 00:28:05,986
Baumer.

284
00:28:09,707 --> 00:28:11,030
Again.

285
00:28:13,428 --> 00:28:14,742
Again.

286
00:28:21,215 --> 00:28:23,133
You'll pay for this, Baumer.

287
00:28:26,260 --> 00:28:27,459
Rirle. Fill your pack.

288
00:28:27,574 --> 00:28:29,856
No, no, Corporal.

289
00:28:29,971 --> 00:28:32,848
You must keep
your eyes open, Corporal.

290
00:30:37,322 --> 00:30:38,646
Attack!

291
00:30:41,158 --> 00:30:42,722
Lay down.

292
00:31:06,218 --> 00:31:08,261
Your training days are over.

293
00:31:09,699 --> 00:31:12,941
You are soldiers now
in the Imperial Army.

294
00:31:19,175 --> 00:31:23,251
In the front lines you will
understand the value and the purpose

295
00:31:23,366 --> 00:31:25,044
of all you've learned here,

296
00:31:25,044 --> 00:31:27,806
everything your officers
have taught you.

297
00:31:28,765 --> 00:31:31,403
Their ways have sometimes
seemed harsh to you,

298
00:31:35,239 --> 00:31:38,241
for the lessons
they taught you in this camp.

299
00:31:39,554 --> 00:31:41,722
They've taught you to be soldiers.

300
00:31:42,077 --> 00:31:45,558
To be soldiers
in the service of Almighty God,

301
00:31:45,558 --> 00:31:48,790
the Kaiser and the Fatherland.

302
00:31:50,468 --> 00:31:54,669
Right...face.

303
00:31:56,347 --> 00:31:59,349
Forward...march.

304
00:32:46,591 --> 00:32:47,915
Forward...march.

305
00:33:15,132 --> 00:33:16,091
Open up.

306
00:34:22,764 --> 00:34:24,078
Shoulder weapons.

307
00:34:29,477 --> 00:34:31,760
Right face.

308
00:34:34,991 --> 00:34:36,910
Board the train.

309
00:35:02,094 --> 00:35:03,293
No smoking.

310
00:35:05,575 --> 00:35:06,889
No smoking.

311
00:35:10,486 --> 00:35:12,289
Fifth company, get down.

312
00:35:12,404 --> 00:35:13,488
Hold up.

313
00:35:16,125 --> 00:35:19,366
Second Company.
This way. Fall out, two ranks.

314
00:35:50,784 --> 00:35:54,017
So... Here you are.

315
00:35:58,093 --> 00:36:02,772
It's the custom to assign
one old hand to every new platoon.

316
00:36:02,888 --> 00:36:04,086
You're the new platoon.

317
00:36:05,046 --> 00:36:06,973
I'm the old hand.

318
00:36:19,201 --> 00:36:21,714
I'll teach you practic...
Listen to me, boy.

319
00:36:22,682 --> 00:36:24,715
I'll teach you practical things.

320
00:36:29,271 --> 00:36:30,469
And how to kill Frenchies.

321
00:36:35,984 --> 00:36:39,350
First we'll give you hot food,
let you get some sleep,

322
00:36:42,822 --> 00:36:43,906
Tonight.

323
00:37:13,885 --> 00:37:15,679
Frenchie wants to say hello.

324
00:37:17,357 --> 00:37:19,275
You just stick close to Kat,

325
00:37:20,838 --> 00:37:22,632
and move when I tell you to move.

326
00:37:34,505 --> 00:37:36,547
Get down. Off the road.

327
00:37:36,662 --> 00:37:39,664
Take cover. Off the road!

328
00:38:07,726 --> 00:38:09,999
Shoot the wounded horses!

329
00:38:10,124 --> 00:38:11,677
Shoot them!

330
00:38:19,599 --> 00:38:21,632
Shoot them, can't you?

331
00:38:22,591 --> 00:38:23,550
Shoot them.

332
00:38:32,661 --> 00:38:35,308
Hey! You're crazy?
You want to kill somebody?

333
00:38:35,423 --> 00:38:36,622
Get down.

334
00:39:00,722 --> 00:39:06,477
Why? What have they done?
They haven't done anything.

335
00:39:08,644 --> 00:39:14,159
Using horses is wrong.
It's wrong killing horses.

336
00:39:20,632 --> 00:39:21,831
Come on, let's go, boys.

337
00:39:23,509 --> 00:39:24,708
Get up.

338
00:39:30,587 --> 00:39:32,984
Up. Come on, boys.

339
00:39:40,062 --> 00:39:41,376
Everybody here?

340
00:39:42,460 --> 00:39:45,097
Huh? Link up, boys.

341
00:39:49,288 --> 00:39:52,050
A taste of the real thing.
You'll get used to it.

342
00:39:53,364 --> 00:39:54,448
You ready?

343
00:39:55,647 --> 00:39:56,730
All right.

344
00:39:59,368 --> 00:40:03,444
Well, you're almost getting
to be soldiers now.

345
00:40:04,758 --> 00:40:07,520
You stick with Kat
and you'll be all right.

346
00:40:22,270 --> 00:40:25,501
'We have been at the front
for a year. We are soldiers now.

347
00:40:25,626 --> 00:40:27,180
'We know this place well.

348
00:40:27,899 --> 00:40:29,587
'We are at home.

349
00:40:29,587 --> 00:40:34,382
'Only Kemmerich is dead but we keep
hearing about others in our class;

350
00:40:34,497 --> 00:40:36,780
'dead, wounded.

351
00:40:42,054 --> 00:40:45,047
'If a shot comes,
all we can do is duck,

352
00:40:45,171 --> 00:40:47,809
'because we can never know
where it will fall.

353
00:40:55,126 --> 00:40:57,879
'I can be smashed to bits
in a bomb-proof dugout,

354
00:40:58,003 --> 00:41:00,996
'of I can survive ten hours
unscathed out in the open.

355
00:41:09,157 --> 00:41:12,514
'Of course, every soldier believes
in chance and trusts his luck.

356
00:41:12,629 --> 00:41:15,266
'But no soldier outlives
a thousand chances.

357
00:41:22,468 --> 00:41:24,262
'We call them corpse rats.

358
00:41:24,387 --> 00:41:27,858
'They have shocking evil faces
and even on our empty stomachs,

359
00:41:27,983 --> 00:41:31,215
'it is nauseating
to see their long naked tais.

360
00:41:37,813 --> 00:41:42,014
'The bait is bread,
so rotten even we won't eat it.

361
00:41:46,569 --> 00:41:49,322
'they'll come among us
to snatch them away.

362
00:41:53,762 --> 00:41:55,565
'It's a way to pass the time.'

363
00:42:09,471 --> 00:42:11,754
Gas masks. Gas masks.

364
00:42:12,713 --> 00:42:16,904
'Gas, the most feared,
most obscene weapon of all.

365
00:42:16,904 --> 00:42:19,905
'We remember the awful sights
in the hospital.

366
00:42:20,385 --> 00:42:22,418
'The gas patients who, surfocating,

367
00:42:22,543 --> 00:42:25,305
'cough up their burned lungs
in clots.

368
00:42:25,420 --> 00:42:27,942
'Better take your chances
in the open

369
00:42:27,942 --> 00:42:32,018
'than stay in the hollows
where the vapours settle.'

370
00:43:34,969 --> 00:43:38,086
'The new recruits are more trouble
than they are worth.

371
00:43:38,211 --> 00:43:41,683
'Between five and ten
get killed to every old hand.

372
00:43:41,807 --> 00:43:44,924
'And they get killed simply
because they are so inexperienced.

373
00:43:49,000 --> 00:43:50,439
No, don't! No!

374
00:43:51,877 --> 00:43:52,961
Get him.

375
00:44:16,103 --> 00:44:19,335
Hand me a rifle. Hand me a rifle.

376
00:44:24,619 --> 00:44:26,058
Kat, wait!

377
00:44:43,205 --> 00:44:44,644
A baby.

378
00:44:47,876 --> 00:44:49,794
Just a baby.

379
00:45:23,494 --> 00:45:24,808
They're in position.

380
00:45:24,933 --> 00:45:26,851
- Nearby?
- Yes, sir.

381
00:45:26,976 --> 00:45:28,529
'How long has it been?

382
00:45:28,654 --> 00:45:33,449
'Weeks, months, years? Only days.

383
00:45:33,564 --> 00:45:36,681
'Yesterday we were under fire.
Today we can rest.

384
00:45:36,806 --> 00:45:39,923
'Tomorrow we go up
to the trenches again.'

385
00:46:04,628 --> 00:46:07,025
Boys, boys, come here.

386
00:46:07,140 --> 00:46:09,778
Look, you boys go on that side.

387
00:46:09,778 --> 00:46:11,456
Over here. This way.

388
00:46:11,581 --> 00:46:12,780
Easy, easy.

389
00:46:16,740 --> 00:46:18,658
Get around, get around up there.

390
00:46:22,255 --> 00:46:23,329
This way.

391
00:46:25,132 --> 00:46:26,206
It's gone.

392
00:46:27,645 --> 00:46:30,646
Quick, he'll get away.
Get him, get him, get him!

393
00:46:48,034 --> 00:46:50,671
Someone eat the liver. I'm on a diet.

394
00:46:58,583 --> 00:47:02,899
and the sturfing would have been
something very special.

395
00:47:03,983 --> 00:47:05,546
But all considered...

396
00:47:05,661 --> 00:47:07,579
A feast. I feel like a king.

397
00:47:07,704 --> 00:47:09,737
Ah, not bad, not bad.

398
00:47:10,696 --> 00:47:13,698
Like I say,
it's not a bad little war.

399
00:47:15,731 --> 00:47:18,253
You never answered
my question, Joseph.

400
00:47:18,253 --> 00:47:20,046
What question?

401
00:47:22,329 --> 00:47:24,372
What we'll all do. Get drunk.

402
00:47:24,487 --> 00:47:26,405
Of course he'll get drunk.

403
00:47:26,645 --> 00:47:29,522
Then it's back home
and mama and all that.

404
00:47:29,646 --> 00:47:31,085
But what ese?

405
00:47:31,200 --> 00:47:33,722
Well, tell him, Joseph.
Don't be ashamed.

406
00:47:33,838 --> 00:47:35,161
I'm not ashamed.

407
00:47:35,516 --> 00:47:38,278
He's going to theology school
to be a minister.

408
00:47:40,436 --> 00:47:44,272
A year here and you haven't changed
your mind about that.

409
00:47:44,397 --> 00:47:46,909
Is God still in his heaven?

410
00:47:47,034 --> 00:47:48,348
Nothing ever changes that.

411
00:47:48,348 --> 00:47:52,069
What about you?
Back to the cobbler's bench, eh?

412
00:47:52,184 --> 00:47:53,623
And the children.

413
00:47:53,747 --> 00:47:55,071
How many you got?

414
00:47:55,071 --> 00:47:57,583
Don't ask.
Good thing I'm a shoemaker,

415
00:47:57,708 --> 00:48:00,345
of I'd go broke just buying shoes.

416
00:48:06,694 --> 00:48:09,572
More coffins.
A bigger load than usual.

417
00:48:09,572 --> 00:48:11,854
That means a bigger offensive.

418
00:48:16,774 --> 00:48:18,692
How considerate
they are at headquarters.

419
00:48:21,444 --> 00:48:23,602
Come on, get this one down.

420
00:48:24,321 --> 00:48:25,645
Haul them up.

421
00:48:42,313 --> 00:48:43,991
Careful, careful.

422
00:48:49,631 --> 00:48:50,590
How old are you?

423
00:48:50,944 --> 00:48:52,143
Sixteen.

424
00:48:54,426 --> 00:48:56,459
Next year, fight out of the cradle.

425
00:49:05,934 --> 00:49:07,497
Did you notch this bayonet?

426
00:49:07,497 --> 00:49:08,456
Yes, sir.

427
00:49:10,375 --> 00:49:11,928
Who told you to?

428
00:49:11,928 --> 00:49:13,971
- At the training camp...
- Training camp, eh?

429
00:49:15,649 --> 00:49:19,965
Sonny, if the enemy ever caught you
with this, they wouldn't kill you,

430
00:49:23,926 --> 00:49:25,844
Nobody uses these things any more.

431
00:49:25,959 --> 00:49:28,961
It's by mutual agreement,
on both sides.

432
00:49:29,076 --> 00:49:30,514
I didn't know.

433
00:49:30,639 --> 00:49:32,432
- First time?
- Yes, sir.

434
00:49:32,557 --> 00:49:35,319
Don't 'sir' me. I'm a private.

435
00:49:35,434 --> 00:49:36,518
Sorry, I thought...

436
00:49:36,633 --> 00:49:38,916
Don't think. Just listen.

437
00:49:39,031 --> 00:49:40,114
Yes, sir.

438
00:49:41,908 --> 00:49:44,066
Your spade is better.

439
00:49:44,190 --> 00:49:47,662
You hit a man under the chin.
Take his head off.

440
00:49:47,787 --> 00:49:50,069
It's a good club, too.

441
00:49:50,184 --> 00:49:51,383
Cos it's heavy.

442
00:49:51,508 --> 00:49:57,137
Hit a man between neck and shoulder.
Right here. Split him right in two.

443
00:49:57,262 --> 00:49:59,295
- Mother of God!
- It's cleaner.

444
00:49:59,420 --> 00:50:01,213
Bayonet gets stuck in ribs,

445
00:50:01,213 --> 00:50:03,371
you have to kick him to pull it out.

446
00:50:04,455 --> 00:50:07,092
Time it takes, you're a dead man.

447
00:50:08,770 --> 00:50:10,334
Understand?

448
00:50:12,846 --> 00:50:16,328
Now, where is your platoon leader?

449
00:50:16,443 --> 00:50:18,601
Corporal Himmestoss
said he'd meet us here.

450
00:50:18,725 --> 00:50:19,684
Ah.

451
00:50:20,758 --> 00:50:21,957
Corporal who?

452
00:50:21,957 --> 00:50:23,405
Himmestoss.

453
00:50:23,520 --> 00:50:24,959
From Oldenberg training station?

454
00:50:25,084 --> 00:50:26,043
Yes, sir.

455
00:50:26,158 --> 00:50:28,076
I don't believe it!

456
00:50:28,200 --> 00:50:31,078
Vengeance is mine.

457
00:50:35,509 --> 00:50:37,427
No, sir. He got into trouble.

458
00:50:37,551 --> 00:50:41,992
Overdid it with two trainees on
the muddy field. You know the field?

459
00:50:42,711 --> 00:50:45,108
Do we know the muddy field?

460
00:50:45,348 --> 00:50:47,746
He went too far. Almost killed them.

461
00:50:47,861 --> 00:50:50,978
He didn't see the son of the local
magistrate watching.

462
00:50:51,103 --> 00:50:54,459
So, he's here.
Of course he'd spoil it for himself.

463
00:50:57,336 --> 00:51:01,297
Oh, Lord. I can hardly wait.

464
00:51:01,412 --> 00:51:05,853
Oh, well. Look who's here.

465
00:51:18,445 --> 00:51:19,883
Well, we meet again.

466
00:51:23,959 --> 00:51:27,316
Kropp, isn't it? You remember me,
Corporal Himmestoss.

467
00:51:27,431 --> 00:51:31,277
Müller, you here too?
Oh, yes, I remember you very well.

468
00:51:32,955 --> 00:51:38,345
Lehr, Behm, Baumer...Baumer.

469
00:51:40,387 --> 00:51:41,826
Nothing wrong with my memory!

470
00:51:48,185 --> 00:51:50,343
You've all managed
to stay alive.

471
00:51:50,343 --> 00:51:51,656
Not Kemmerich.

472
00:51:51,781 --> 00:51:55,857
Kemmerich?
I don't remember Kemmerich.

473
00:51:55,857 --> 00:51:59,089
The rest of you seem to have learned
your lessons pretty well.

474
00:52:03,769 --> 00:52:05,447
don't you turn your back.

475
00:52:06,406 --> 00:52:07,490
What did you say?

476
00:52:10,127 --> 00:52:13,120
So this is the great
Corporal Himmestoss?

477
00:52:13,244 --> 00:52:14,923
And who are you?

478
00:52:16,121 --> 00:52:17,675
I asked you a question, soldier.

479
00:52:19,478 --> 00:52:24,273
Himmestoss.
There's a latfine down the road.

480
00:52:24,273 --> 00:52:26,431
Why don't you take a jump?

481
00:52:31,226 --> 00:52:33,029
Do you want to be court martialled?

482
00:52:35,552 --> 00:52:37,105
Stand up straight, hees together,

483
00:52:37,105 --> 00:52:38,908
when your superior officer
speaks to you.

484
00:52:39,743 --> 00:52:41,421
All of you!

485
00:52:46,935 --> 00:52:49,573
Squad, attention!

486
00:52:52,814 --> 00:52:54,732
Right...face.

487
00:52:56,650 --> 00:52:59,288
Right turn, forward...march.

488
00:52:59,288 --> 00:53:03,364
Left, left, left, left.

489
00:53:03,364 --> 00:53:07,200
Left, left,
left, left, left, left.

490
00:53:23,033 --> 00:53:25,796
Easy, boy, easy.
It'll be all right.

491
00:53:47,134 --> 00:53:52,649
Ah, you see the way he blows up?
Boom, like that.

492
00:53:54,567 --> 00:53:56,130
Want to kill Frenchmen?

493
00:54:23,108 --> 00:54:25,151
You'll be all right, boy.

494
00:54:25,630 --> 00:54:27,069
You'll get used to it.

495
00:54:31,030 --> 00:54:33,907
To soften us up so we can't sleep.

496
00:54:33,907 --> 00:54:35,345
Huh, then when they attack,

497
00:54:35,700 --> 00:54:39,296
we won't be able to fight back
because we're too tired.

498
00:54:40,140 --> 00:54:43,497
Two days and nights. How much longer?

499
00:54:43,977 --> 00:54:46,614
Not too long, not too long.

500
00:54:46,614 --> 00:54:48,292
Why don't they stop?

501
00:55:06,639 --> 00:55:08,077
Where are you going?

502
00:55:08,077 --> 00:55:10,235
I'll be back...in a minute.

503
00:55:10,235 --> 00:55:14,676
No, just relax. Wait. It'll be over
soon. Come on, sit down and relax.

504
00:55:17,668 --> 00:55:21,034
Let me go. I must get away.

505
00:55:28,102 --> 00:55:30,020
Sit down and calm down.

506
00:55:30,145 --> 00:55:34,096
Now, go and sit down.
Behave yourselves. Be easy, quiet.

507
00:55:35,419 --> 00:55:36,858
I said...

508
00:55:44,415 --> 00:55:48,491
Come on, let's go.
Come on...come on.

509
00:56:02,877 --> 00:56:06,234
'No longer do we lie helpless,
awaiting destruction.

510
00:56:06,234 --> 00:56:10,914
'We can destroy and kill
to save ourselves and to be revenged.

511
00:56:13,916 --> 00:56:17,032
'When we see their faces,
we become wild beasts.

512
00:56:17,147 --> 00:56:19,190
'We turn into thugs and murderers.

513
00:56:19,190 --> 00:56:21,108
'Into God only knows what devis.

514
00:56:22,307 --> 00:56:24,100
'If your own father was with them,

515
00:57:13,270 --> 00:57:14,229
Forward!

516
00:57:23,705 --> 00:57:24,664
Fire.

517
00:57:28,135 --> 00:57:29,814
What the hell is this?

518
00:57:29,938 --> 00:57:32,461
Come on, let's go. Come on, you all.

519
00:57:32,576 --> 00:57:34,619
Come on, move. You too, soldier.

520
00:57:36,412 --> 00:57:40,008
Come on, let's go.
let's go, let's go.

521
00:57:40,008 --> 00:57:41,572
What's happening down there?

522
00:57:42,770 --> 00:57:43,844
Come on.

523
00:57:46,127 --> 00:57:47,441
Come on!

524
00:57:48,764 --> 00:57:49,848
Come on!

525
00:57:50,682 --> 00:57:55,957
'How long is it? Days,
of weeks, of months, of years?

526
00:57:56,082 --> 00:57:59,438
'Attack, counter-attack.
And the dead pile up.

527
00:57:59,554 --> 00:58:04,589
'Winter, summer... The days are hot
and the dead lie unburied.

528
00:58:04,713 --> 00:58:06,276
'The shels will bury them.

529
00:58:06,391 --> 00:58:10,228
'But when the wind blows,
it brings the smell of blood,

530
00:58:10,352 --> 00:58:12,625
'which is heavy and sweet.'

531
01:03:32,197 --> 01:03:34,719
No, shh...shh...

532
01:03:36,522 --> 01:03:38,440
Shh! Shh!

533
01:03:38,440 --> 01:03:40,233
No, no...

534
01:03:42,391 --> 01:03:46,112
- No, shh. Je vous...

535
01:03:46,227 --> 01:03:49,824
Je vous...help...
I want to help you.

536
01:04:42,235 --> 01:04:43,789
Ohh!

537
01:04:59,623 --> 01:05:02,135
I didn't want to kill you.

538
01:05:05,617 --> 01:05:08,609
But you jumped in here like that.

539
01:05:10,172 --> 01:05:14,248
What would you have done? It's...

540
01:05:20,846 --> 01:05:22,400
face to face.

541
01:05:25,277 --> 01:05:27,435
I just saw your rifle...

542
01:05:29,478 --> 01:05:31,396
your bayonet...

543
01:05:33,314 --> 01:05:35,117
grenades.

544
01:05:38,713 --> 01:05:41,351
If we threw all those away...

545
01:05:44,103 --> 01:05:46,021
we could be brothers.

546
01:05:48,908 --> 01:05:52,859
But they never want us
to know that, do they?

547
01:05:55,736 --> 01:05:58,134
They never want us to know.

548
01:06:00,052 --> 01:06:02,689
We each have mothers...

549
01:06:03,897 --> 01:06:05,576
fathers...

550
01:06:07,734 --> 01:06:09,527
the same...

551
01:06:10,726 --> 01:06:12,644
fear of death.

552
01:06:15,406 --> 01:06:17,199
The same...

553
01:06:18,523 --> 01:06:20,086
pain.

554
01:06:21,765 --> 01:06:23,443
The same...

555
01:06:25,476 --> 01:06:27,039
everything.

556
01:06:30,875 --> 01:06:32,429
Everything.

557
01:06:41,185 --> 01:06:43,228
Forgive me, comfade.

558
01:06:57,978 --> 01:07:01,095
I could write...to your family.

559
01:07:03,252 --> 01:07:04,691
Yes...

560
01:07:04,691 --> 01:07:06,964
Yes, I'll write!

561
01:07:29,396 --> 01:07:33,232
'Gefard Duval, compositeur.

562
01:07:33,232 --> 01:07:36,589
'I have killed
Gefard Duval the printer.'

563
01:08:37,862 --> 01:08:41,218
Battalion, attention!

564
01:08:44,335 --> 01:08:46,973
Present arms!

565
01:08:52,373 --> 01:08:54,655
Eyes left!

566
01:10:02,046 --> 01:10:03,964
Battalion Commander, sir.

567
01:10:04,080 --> 01:10:07,561
Your Majesty, I have the honour
to bring you the salute

568
01:10:07,676 --> 01:10:10,562
of the 150th Infantry Battalion.

569
01:10:25,907 --> 01:10:29,504
Your Majesty,
Soldier Bernard.

570
01:10:43,659 --> 01:10:46,651
Your Majesty,
Soldier Langer.

571
01:11:04,998 --> 01:11:08,000
Your Majesty,
Corporal Himmestoss.

572
01:11:20,947 --> 01:11:23,104
Battalion! At ease!

573
01:11:24,907 --> 01:11:29,942
Officers, non-commissioned officers,
enlisted men.

574
01:11:30,058 --> 01:11:33,664
The men who have received decorations
this day

575
01:11:41,930 --> 01:11:48,164
From this day on, your Kaiser urges
you all to aspire to such strength,

576
01:11:48,164 --> 01:11:54,407
to such bravery, to such obedience
to your God and your country.

577
01:11:54,522 --> 01:11:57,639
If you do, my soldiers,

578
01:11:57,639 --> 01:12:01,955
I am certain you will all
one day wear a medal

579
01:12:02,080 --> 01:12:04,353
pinned on you by your Kaiser.

580
01:12:04,353 --> 01:12:08,199
You have all done your duty
as noble German warriors.

581
01:12:08,199 --> 01:12:11,795
You have shown the world our might.

582
01:12:11,910 --> 01:12:15,986
You have stricken
our enemies with fear.

583
01:12:25,106 --> 01:12:27,983
It'll take weeks
to get to the skin!

584
01:12:28,099 --> 01:12:31,340
- Give me that soap?
- How's the water?

585
01:12:31,456 --> 01:12:33,374
Beautiful! Come on in!

586
01:12:33,498 --> 01:12:36,135
Hey! Look at that!

587
01:12:40,691 --> 01:12:45,371
Hello! Bonjour, bonjour!
Jolies! Jolies!

588
01:12:45,486 --> 01:12:48,967
Somebody do something!
Just don't let them get away!

589
01:12:49,083 --> 01:12:53,158
Allo, Mademoiselles!
Allo, Mademoiselles!

590
01:12:53,158 --> 01:12:54,961
Attendez, s'il vous plait!

591
01:12:55,076 --> 01:12:57,004
Tell them to come over.

592
01:12:57,119 --> 01:13:01,435
Er, yes, er... Mademoiselle,
you come over this side, oui?

593
01:13:03,833 --> 01:13:06,594
- We want to talk.
- Talk?!

594
01:13:06,709 --> 01:13:08,512
Parlez vous, Mademoiselles!

595
01:13:08,512 --> 01:13:11,025
Hey! Hey, wait a minute!

596
01:13:11,025 --> 01:13:13,308
Frauleins, l'amour, yes?

597
01:13:13,308 --> 01:13:16,904
You coming over,
we have l'amour, yes?

598
01:13:16,904 --> 01:13:18,947
Oui, oui, oui.

599
01:13:19,062 --> 01:13:21,824
- Don't go!
- Yoo-hoo!

600
01:13:21,939 --> 01:13:26,254
Gifs! Fraulein, bread, yes?
You want bread?

601
01:13:26,254 --> 01:13:29,017
Look! Regardez!

602
01:13:29,142 --> 01:13:32,258
Yum-yum-yum-yum-yum, yes? Bread!

603
01:13:32,258 --> 01:13:34,291
You come over here, oui?

604
01:13:35,136 --> 01:13:36,574
Vous!

605
01:13:36,574 --> 01:13:38,013
Venez!

606
01:13:38,128 --> 01:13:39,451
Ici!

607
01:13:39,566 --> 01:13:41,849
Ce soir!

608
01:13:41,964 --> 01:13:44,122
Vous venez!

609
01:13:45,206 --> 01:13:46,769
Lá-bas!

610
01:13:46,884 --> 01:13:48,687
Nótre maison!

611
01:13:48,802 --> 01:13:52,283
They want us to come
to their house tonight!

612
01:13:52,398 --> 01:13:55,755
Oui! Avec quelque chose
a manger, oui?

613
01:13:55,755 --> 01:13:59,236
- With something to eat!
- La maison lá!

614
01:13:59,236 --> 01:14:01,030
Maison!

615
01:14:01,030 --> 01:14:05,470
- Bonjour! Bonjour! Bonjour!
- Bye! Bye!

616
01:14:12,787 --> 01:14:14,581
Drink up, Tjaden.

617
01:14:21,658 --> 01:14:25,734
It's bad luck there's four of us
and three of them.

618
01:14:25,859 --> 01:14:28,611
Mm-hmm... Bad luck.

619
01:14:28,736 --> 01:14:31,853
See, it's just not fair
to the gifs.

620
01:14:31,968 --> 01:14:36,169
Drink up, Tjaden. How often
do you get good French wine?

621
01:14:36,293 --> 01:14:40,245
Not fair to the gifs... No.

622
01:14:40,245 --> 01:14:44,561
One of us will have to make
the supreme sacrifice.

623
01:14:44,685 --> 01:14:46,239
Mmm?

624
01:14:46,363 --> 01:14:50,075
Bottoms up, Tjaden,
you're not keeping up with us.

625
01:14:53,316 --> 01:14:55,954
Maybe we should draw lots?

626
01:14:59,195 --> 01:15:00,989
You lose.

627
01:15:44,884 --> 01:15:46,917
- Bonsoir.
- Bonsoir.

628
01:16:33,450 --> 01:16:36,442
This looks like
the right line-up, huh?

629
01:16:36,442 --> 01:16:38,964
I'm all for this one.

630
01:16:39,079 --> 01:16:41,477
You like yours, Albert?

631
01:16:41,477 --> 01:16:43,395
Yes.

632
01:16:43,520 --> 01:16:44,833
Paul?

633
01:17:24,289 --> 01:17:26,446
Mais tu es blanc comme neige,
je crois.

634
01:17:26,571 --> 01:17:27,885
Er...

635
01:17:30,647 --> 01:17:32,565
Est-ce que je me trompe,
petit bon homme.

636
01:17:32,680 --> 01:17:34,003
Oui!

637
01:18:25,926 --> 01:18:27,125
Mon petit soldat.

638
01:18:39,113 --> 01:18:40,196
Non, non. Ici.

639
01:18:52,185 --> 01:18:54,582
- Quelle age a-tu?
- Eh?

640
01:18:54,707 --> 01:18:56,625
- Ton age?
- No...

641
01:18:56,740 --> 01:18:59,742
- Quelle age a-tu?
- Ah! I'm 19.

642
01:19:00,940 --> 01:19:02,024
19...

643
01:19:03,338 --> 01:19:04,901
19... Oh!

644
01:19:13,168 --> 01:19:16,410
Vingt-cinq ans? Vraiment?

645
01:20:35,435 --> 01:20:39,511
Look out! Look out! Take cover!

646
01:21:54,814 --> 01:21:57,816
- My leg!
- Come on, Albert! Up! Up!

647
01:22:03,695 --> 01:22:06,448
Come on, boys,
a little bit more.

648
01:22:23,480 --> 01:22:25,273
Down! Stay down!

649
01:23:10,483 --> 01:23:12,161
I'll be right back!

650
01:23:45,977 --> 01:23:47,300
Hey!

651
01:24:08,044 --> 01:24:09,243
Paul!

652
01:24:11,525 --> 01:24:12,964
Take care!

653
01:24:25,067 --> 01:24:26,746
Kat.

654
01:24:32,864 --> 01:24:34,187
Kat!

655
01:24:34,303 --> 01:24:35,981
Kat, come on!

656
01:24:42,819 --> 01:24:44,977
- All right.
- Easy, easy.

657
01:24:58,643 --> 01:25:01,050
- From Kat.
- What is it?

658
01:25:01,166 --> 01:25:04,762
- It's a long ride.
- Oh, bread and cheese!

659
01:25:05,846 --> 01:25:09,921
He could find a lobster dinner
in the middle of the desert!

660
01:25:12,559 --> 01:25:14,237
Goodbye.

661
01:25:14,237 --> 01:25:16,395
- Take care, Paul.
- Bye.

662
01:25:43,258 --> 01:25:46,490
'Albert and I
are in a Catholic hospital.

663
01:26:48,607 --> 01:26:51,724
- Won't see him again.
- Why not?

664
01:26:56,039 --> 01:26:58,082
The "Dead Room"?

665
01:26:58,082 --> 01:27:00,479
What's the Dead Room?

666
01:27:00,479 --> 01:27:03,356
The Dying Room,
whatever you call it.

667
01:27:03,481 --> 01:27:05,515
It's in the basement.

668
01:27:11,633 --> 01:27:15,594
It's convenient really.
It's next to the mortuary.

669
01:27:16,908 --> 01:27:18,586
No one ever comes back.

670
01:27:25,540 --> 01:27:30,104
'The beds empty quickly,
and new occupants take their places.

671
01:27:30,220 --> 01:27:34,420
'It is going badly with Albert.
He is in much pain.

672
01:27:34,535 --> 01:27:38,496
'Last night one of our wardmates
awakened with a severe haemoffhage.

673
01:28:05,474 --> 01:28:08,830
They won't take me! No! NO!

674
01:28:08,956 --> 01:28:12,187
We're taking you
to the bandaging room.

675
01:28:12,312 --> 01:28:15,429
I won't go to the Dying Room!

676
01:28:15,429 --> 01:28:17,461
We're not going there.

677
01:28:17,461 --> 01:28:19,390
Then why take his tunic?

678
01:28:19,390 --> 01:28:24,060
- I'll be back. I won't die!
- Why are you taking his tunic?

679
01:28:24,185 --> 01:28:27,781
I'll come back!
I won't die! I'll come back!

680
01:28:27,896 --> 01:28:29,220
Liars!

681
01:28:29,335 --> 01:28:31,013
They're lying.

682
01:28:31,138 --> 01:28:33,056
LIARS!

683
01:28:35,933 --> 01:28:40,728
I'll come back!
I'll come back! I won't die...

684
01:28:55,603 --> 01:28:57,396
Stop it!

685
01:28:57,521 --> 01:29:00,877
Stop it! Stop that! Orderly!

686
01:29:00,877 --> 01:29:03,035
Get the orderly! Doctor!

687
01:29:03,150 --> 01:29:05,193
Orderly! Orderly!

688
01:29:24,614 --> 01:29:27,261
Why didn't you leave him alone?

689
01:29:41,886 --> 01:29:44,763
You are doing so well, Paul.

690
01:29:44,888 --> 01:29:47,161
Soon we'll throw away the cane.

691
01:29:51,716 --> 01:29:53,874
- Sister.
- Yes?

692
01:29:55,313 --> 01:29:57,231
I'm worried about my friend.

693
01:29:58,679 --> 01:30:02,870
I think...he is making
a very good recovery.

694
01:30:02,995 --> 01:30:05,392
He worries me.

695
01:30:05,507 --> 01:30:08,145
Since the operation, he...

696
01:30:08,269 --> 01:30:13,180
He's in a terrible state of mind.
He hardly speaks to me any more.

697
01:30:13,304 --> 01:30:18,704
There is always such a reaction after
an amputation.

698
01:30:18,704 --> 01:30:20,497
Always!

699
01:30:20,622 --> 01:30:23,499
Now, stop worrying.

700
01:30:23,614 --> 01:30:25,896
Albert will get over it.

701
01:30:26,011 --> 01:30:28,649
Go, tell him your good news.

702
01:30:28,774 --> 01:30:30,816
That should cheer him up.

703
01:30:46,641 --> 01:30:48,204
Albert?

704
01:30:48,319 --> 01:30:50,237
How do you feel?

705
01:31:05,946 --> 01:31:11,460
Albert, they're giving me 16 days
convalescent leave. I'm going home.

706
01:31:13,023 --> 01:31:15,296
They'll be sending you home, too.

707
01:31:15,421 --> 01:31:18,174
Is there anything I can get you?

708
01:31:19,497 --> 01:31:20,936
A gun.

709
01:31:25,376 --> 01:31:26,814
A what?

710
01:31:28,848 --> 01:31:32,924
You want to get me something?
Get me a gun.

711
01:31:37,249 --> 01:31:41,680
- Will you get me a gun or not?
- No! Don't talk nonsense!

712
01:31:41,805 --> 01:31:45,161
No, you talk sense.

713
01:31:50,676 --> 01:31:52,229
Albert...

714
01:31:55,471 --> 01:31:56,794
I'm sorry.

715
01:34:04,020 --> 01:34:05,344
Paul?

716
01:34:05,459 --> 01:34:10,139
Paul! Why didn't you tell us
you were coming?

717
01:34:10,254 --> 01:34:12,652
Mother. Mother!

718
01:34:30,759 --> 01:34:34,115
Paul? Come up.

719
01:34:52,346 --> 01:34:54,380
Give me your handkerchief.

720
01:35:12,976 --> 01:35:14,529
How is she?

721
01:35:16,687 --> 01:35:18,730
She's in bed.

722
01:35:18,730 --> 01:35:20,763
She's sick, Paul.

723
01:35:21,847 --> 01:35:23,765
What is it?

724
01:35:23,880 --> 01:35:25,798
We don't know.

725
01:35:25,923 --> 01:35:32,396
But...Dr Bradermeier thinks...
it's probably the cancer again.

726
01:36:07,411 --> 01:36:09,089
Thank God.

727
01:36:11,726 --> 01:36:13,884
Oh, thank God.

728
01:36:16,886 --> 01:36:18,689
Thank God.

729
01:36:20,367 --> 01:36:22,161
Are you wounded, Paul?

730
01:36:24,559 --> 01:36:27,675
No... No, I'm just on leave.

731
01:36:29,114 --> 01:36:31,396
- Oh, Paul.
- How are you?

732
01:36:31,512 --> 01:36:36,076
I'm going to try to get up
a little today, I think.

733
01:36:36,191 --> 01:36:37,515
Good.

734
01:36:43,864 --> 01:36:46,386
My Paul.

735
01:36:48,784 --> 01:36:50,586
My Paul.

736
01:36:52,504 --> 01:36:53,818
Look.

737
01:36:58,019 --> 01:36:59,333
Bread.

738
01:37:01,136 --> 01:37:05,087
And cheese and...butter!

739
01:37:07,370 --> 01:37:10,007
They feed you enough where you are?

740
01:37:10,132 --> 01:37:12,770
Not always enough, but we manage.

741
01:37:14,083 --> 01:37:16,126
Is it very bad there?

742
01:37:18,159 --> 01:37:19,483
No.

743
01:37:19,598 --> 01:37:21,516
Not so bad.

744
01:37:21,641 --> 01:37:24,518
Heinrich Bradermeier was here

745
01:37:24,642 --> 01:37:30,272
and said it's terrible out there,
with the gas attacks

746
01:37:30,396 --> 01:37:32,554
and all the rest of it.

747
01:37:32,669 --> 01:37:34,232
It's just talk.

748
01:37:34,232 --> 01:37:36,266
Just talk.

749
01:37:36,391 --> 01:37:39,383
Look at me, I'm well and fit,

750
01:37:39,507 --> 01:37:41,070
aren't I?

751
01:37:43,468 --> 01:37:44,782
Yes.

752
01:37:51,255 --> 01:37:53,298
But then...

753
01:38:00,012 --> 01:38:02,534
It's more comfortable,
Father, that's all.

754
01:38:02,649 --> 01:38:06,370
But I...I want to show off
our soldier boy

755
01:38:06,485 --> 01:38:08,643
to the fellows at Max's.

756
01:38:22,079 --> 01:38:26,155
You look well, Paul. Fit.
War agrees with you, eh?

757
01:38:27,229 --> 01:38:30,950
- I suppose, in a way.
- Have a cigar.

758
01:38:31,075 --> 01:38:35,266
If you're old enough
to kill Frenchmen, you can smoke.

759
01:38:35,391 --> 01:38:38,747
Hans, another beer
for our young warrior.

760
01:38:38,862 --> 01:38:42,219
What's the spirit like out there?
Excellent, eh?

761
01:38:45,940 --> 01:38:49,537
The enemy has many reserves,
Mr Hollerstein.

762
01:38:52,893 --> 01:38:55,291
You only see your little sector,

763
01:38:58,887 --> 01:39:04,046
The important thing is
the breakthrough, here in Flanders.

764
01:39:04,171 --> 01:39:06,569
This is Frenchie, this is us.

765
01:39:06,569 --> 01:39:10,760
We have to come found
the Belgian side and fam through.

766
01:39:10,884 --> 01:39:12,678
There's no other way.

767
01:39:12,803 --> 01:39:16,514
Before we beat them
on the Hindenburg line?

768
01:39:16,639 --> 01:39:19,036
It is borders that are important.

769
01:39:19,161 --> 01:39:20,715
You're quite wrong.

770
01:39:20,839 --> 01:39:24,311
Good soldiers never stay
planted on borders like turnips...

771
01:39:35,464 --> 01:39:41,583
You're lying to me, Paul.
I know you are.

772
01:39:42,782 --> 01:39:45,055
I swear to you, he died instantly.

773
01:39:46,254 --> 01:39:49,850
- You promised he wouldn't get hurt.
- Mrs Kemmerich, I...

774
01:39:49,975 --> 01:39:53,812
Why are you living
when he is dead? Why?

775
01:39:53,936 --> 01:39:55,854
What right have you?

776
01:40:13,117 --> 01:40:14,795
Tell me again.

777
01:40:18,276 --> 01:40:20,674
Did you...see it?

778
01:40:20,674 --> 01:40:24,270
Yes, I was fight there next to him.

779
01:40:24,395 --> 01:40:27,512
He died at once. He never suffered.

780
01:40:32,067 --> 01:40:35,424
I know that
you're trying to comfort me,

781
01:40:43,701 --> 01:40:45,619
I want to know the...

782
01:40:45,733 --> 01:40:48,256
I want the truth!

783
01:40:51,373 --> 01:40:53,291
I have to hear it!

784
01:40:55,324 --> 01:40:58,806
Mrs Kemmerich, I promise,
that's exactly how it happened.

785
01:41:05,039 --> 01:41:06,958
His face was quite calm.

786
01:41:07,082 --> 01:41:10,314
- Do you swear it?
- Yes.

787
01:41:11,397 --> 01:41:14,035
By everything that is sacred to you?

788
01:41:22,187 --> 01:41:25,188
By everything that is sacred to me.

789
01:41:25,188 --> 01:41:27,222
He died at once.

790
01:41:44,254 --> 01:41:46,287
May I never come back...

791
01:41:47,736 --> 01:41:50,133
if he wasn't killed instantly.

792
01:41:56,242 --> 01:41:59,004
Carry that lesson to the front lines

793
01:42:03,800 --> 01:42:05,478
You are dismissed.

794
01:42:26,586 --> 01:42:27,785
Baumer.

795
01:42:32,216 --> 01:42:34,134
Paul Baumer!

796
01:42:36,416 --> 01:42:37,979
Baumer!

797
01:42:39,533 --> 01:42:43,130
- Here, have a cigarette.
- No, thank you.

798
01:42:43,130 --> 01:42:47,206
You still haven't picked up
the habit. Well, that's good.

799
01:42:47,330 --> 01:42:51,521
It's not a good habit
but a man has to have vices.

800
01:42:51,646 --> 01:42:55,722
How does it go? All work
and no play... You remember?

801
01:42:57,045 --> 01:43:01,841
How is it, Baumer?
How...how is the spirit?

802
01:43:01,956 --> 01:43:04,113
Excellent, eh? Excellent?

803
01:43:05,312 --> 01:43:06,750
Behm is dead.

804
01:43:06,750 --> 01:43:08,314
Behm?

805
01:43:09,273 --> 01:43:11,076
Josef Behm.

806
01:43:11,076 --> 01:43:14,433
Oh. You know,
I didn't think he would enlist.

807
01:43:14,548 --> 01:43:16,466
But he went.

808
01:43:17,550 --> 01:43:19,104
Yes...

809
01:43:19,228 --> 01:43:21,625
Kemmerich is dead, too.

810
01:43:21,625 --> 01:43:23,064
I was told.

811
01:43:23,179 --> 01:43:26,066
And Kropp has lost a leg.

812
01:43:26,181 --> 01:43:29,422
Er... Oh, Albert Kropp, yes.

813
01:43:30,621 --> 01:43:36,615
I don't know about all the others. We
were separated, but Leer's alive

814
01:43:36,730 --> 01:43:39,493
and Müller is alive and I'm alive.

815
01:43:39,607 --> 01:43:41,526
I'm glad to hear that.

816
01:43:43,693 --> 01:43:45,726
Tell them...

817
01:43:45,851 --> 01:43:51,720
Tell them I'm proud to have
taught them to be good Germans.

818
01:43:51,845 --> 01:43:57,359
To know that you have all
done your duty by the Fatherland.

819
01:43:59,642 --> 01:44:02,279
Imagine how that makes me feel?

820
01:44:03,833 --> 01:44:06,950
You were a good class. Good boys.

821
01:44:06,950 --> 01:44:09,347
Good boys all.

822
01:44:09,347 --> 01:44:13,184
- And this class?
- This lot?

823
01:44:18,708 --> 01:44:21,825
They haven't got your spirit, Baumer.

824
01:44:21,940 --> 01:44:24,577
Not the Iron Youth, eh?

825
01:44:24,702 --> 01:44:26,255
Mm? I'm sorry...?

826
01:44:26,255 --> 01:44:28,059
No Iron Heroes?

827
01:44:28,173 --> 01:44:29,497
Just boys.

828
01:44:31,051 --> 01:44:32,854
Want to play.

829
01:44:32,978 --> 01:44:34,532
Laugh.

830
01:44:35,491 --> 01:44:37,054
To stay alive.

831
01:44:40,286 --> 01:44:41,725
Only boys.

832
01:45:23,941 --> 01:45:26,579
Mother, it's late.
You should be asleep.

833
01:45:26,579 --> 01:45:29,936
Did I wake you, dear? I'm sorry.

834
01:45:29,936 --> 01:45:32,208
You'll catch cold here. Go sleep.

835
01:45:32,333 --> 01:45:34,366
I can sleep enough later.

836
01:45:36,284 --> 01:45:39,171
Are you very much afraid?

837
01:45:41,329 --> 01:45:42,643
No.

838
01:45:42,768 --> 01:45:48,397
I'd like to tell you to be on your
guard against the women in France.

839
01:45:48,521 --> 01:45:50,200
They're no good.

840
01:45:52,233 --> 01:45:56,673
Mother, where we are
there aren't any women.

841
01:45:59,915 --> 01:46:04,470
- Yes, I will.
- I pray for you every day.

842
01:46:04,585 --> 01:46:06,504
I know, Mother.

843
01:46:08,546 --> 01:46:12,382
Perhaps you can get a job
that is not so dangerous?

844
01:46:13,582 --> 01:46:17,062
Perhaps in the cookhouse.
That could be easily done.

845
01:46:17,062 --> 01:46:20,534
Do it, then,
and if others say anything...

846
01:46:20,659 --> 01:46:22,817
I won't let that bother me.

847
01:46:22,817 --> 01:46:25,330
Now, you must sleep,
Mother. Come on.

848
01:46:56,988 --> 01:47:02,627
'Mother, I used to live in this
room. All my things are here.

849
01:47:02,751 --> 01:47:04,909
'All my books, my beloved books,

850
01:47:05,024 --> 01:47:09,225
'but they no longer speak to me
as they used to,

851
01:47:09,225 --> 01:47:13,416
'for I am not what I was
when I lived here.

852
01:47:13,541 --> 01:47:18,336
'I am a soldier. My business
is not reading, it is killing.

853
01:47:18,460 --> 01:47:21,453
'My knowledge of life
is limited to death,

854
01:47:21,577 --> 01:47:25,289
'and I know now
I should never have come back.

855
01:47:29,729 --> 01:47:31,887
'because it has no meaning.

856
01:47:31,887 --> 01:47:36,088
'My companions at the front
are the only truth I know.

857
01:47:40,403 --> 01:47:44,594
'I depend on them
and I depend on nothing ese.

858
01:47:44,719 --> 01:47:48,430
'Mother,
it's a terrible thing to say,

859
01:47:48,430 --> 01:47:52,996
'but I feel I am now going back
to my real home.'

860
01:48:10,498 --> 01:48:11,937
Paul!

861
01:48:21,891 --> 01:48:25,728
- Well, you're back, my boy.
- Yes, I'm back.

862
01:48:28,489 --> 01:48:32,326
You're a fool.
I'm glad to see you, anyway.

863
01:48:32,441 --> 01:48:34,838
I'm glad to see you, too, Kat.

864
01:48:37,715 --> 01:48:40,238
They're getting
younger and younger, Paul.

865
01:48:43,834 --> 01:48:47,316
Our hands'll be full
just taking care of them.

866
01:48:55,468 --> 01:48:58,105
Hey! The old deserter's back!

867
01:49:01,586 --> 01:49:04,579
- How was your leave?
- Good. Where's Müller?

868
01:49:09,019 --> 01:49:12,260
- When was it?
- A week ago.

869
01:49:15,732 --> 01:49:17,170
Was it quick?

870
01:49:21,966 --> 01:49:26,166
Shrapnel in the stomach.
He lasted two hours.

871
01:49:37,080 --> 01:49:38,758
Damn!

872
01:49:58,064 --> 01:49:59,502
Lieutenant!

873
01:50:26,125 --> 01:50:27,679
Lieutenant!

874
01:50:27,804 --> 01:50:31,880
Leer! No, leave him!
He's gone! He's gone!

875
01:50:31,995 --> 01:50:34,642
Leer! Come back!

876
01:50:50,466 --> 01:50:52,029
God!

877
01:50:52,144 --> 01:50:55,865
Oh, GOD! GOD! GOD! GOD!

878
01:51:42,513 --> 01:51:45,266
- Ready! Charge!
- Let's go!

879
01:52:09,126 --> 01:52:13,691
'There isn't much. We are all
going hungry. We are all tired.

880
01:52:13,806 --> 01:52:17,528
'We are all hopeless.
But the war goes on.'

881
01:52:20,280 --> 01:52:22,917
Why don't they just let it end?

882
01:52:22,917 --> 01:52:24,480
Ah, who knows?

883
01:52:27,233 --> 01:52:28,796
We're finished.

884
01:52:33,477 --> 01:52:36,833
Our bread is nothing but sawdust.

885
01:52:39,710 --> 01:52:43,067
You see anybody that hasn't got
dysentery and colic?

886
01:52:43,182 --> 01:52:46,059
Artillery's burned out.

887
01:52:46,184 --> 01:52:48,581
Damned barres are so worn down

888
01:52:58,891 --> 01:53:02,727
Too many guns, tanks.
Now the Americans are pouring in.

889
01:53:04,175 --> 01:53:08,126
New guns, aeroplanes, fresh troops.

890
01:53:25,514 --> 01:53:27,077
Lie still.

891
01:53:28,151 --> 01:53:31,028
- Just as it's ending!
- Be quiet!

892
01:53:31,028 --> 01:53:34,030
- After four years.
- Stretcher!

893
01:53:34,145 --> 01:53:37,147
- Stretcher bearer!
- Just as it's ending.

894
01:53:38,586 --> 01:53:40,744
It's all right. Just lie still.

895
01:53:40,868 --> 01:53:43,745
Don't worry,
it looks like a clean wound.

896
01:53:43,860 --> 01:53:45,663
Just hold on.

897
01:53:50,574 --> 01:53:52,252
Stretcher!

898
01:53:52,376 --> 01:53:54,535
Can you stand up?

899
01:53:54,659 --> 01:53:56,577
You can get up?

900
01:53:58,016 --> 01:54:01,248
Come on. Come on! Come on!

901
01:54:08,680 --> 01:54:10,608
I've got to carry you.

902
01:54:11,682 --> 01:54:13,485
Ready? Up.

903
01:54:35,303 --> 01:54:36,742
Sorry.

904
01:54:36,742 --> 01:54:39,379
That's all right. That's all right.

905
01:54:48,500 --> 01:54:51,377
We gotta keep going. You ready?

906
01:54:51,492 --> 01:54:53,170
Yes, yes.

907
01:54:54,849 --> 01:54:56,412
Come on.

908
01:55:00,133 --> 01:55:02,530
- You got it?
- I'll try.

909
01:55:06,481 --> 01:55:08,640
- No.
- No, I'll try.

910
01:55:08,764 --> 01:55:11,162
No, you can't. It's all right.

911
01:56:15,072 --> 01:56:16,511
No.

912
01:56:18,313 --> 01:56:22,754
It's his shin, he's fainted.

913
01:56:24,308 --> 01:56:26,590
C'mon, Kat, come on.

914
01:56:47,095 --> 01:56:49,367
He was talking.

915
01:56:53,683 --> 01:56:55,611
Ten minutes ago.

916
01:57:01,241 --> 01:57:03,159
We were talking.

917
01:57:25,581 --> 01:57:29,906
'It is Autumn.
We wait for the end.

918
01:57:29,906 --> 01:57:32,658
'We wait for the Armistice.

919
01:57:32,783 --> 01:57:34,701
'We wait for peace.'

920
01:57:54,361 --> 01:57:57,124
'a bullet in the head.

921
01:57:57,124 --> 01:58:00,241
'Himmestoss was killed
the same day

922
01:58:00,241 --> 01:58:02,878
'and now Detering is gone.

923
01:58:04,556 --> 01:58:08,038
'I think we started
to lose Detering last spring,

924
01:58:08,038 --> 01:58:10,915
'when the apple trees
came into bloom.

925
01:58:11,030 --> 01:58:14,271
'You know that expression of his
in springtime?

926
01:58:19,431 --> 01:58:23,382
'A week later he was caught
by the Military Police.

927
01:58:23,507 --> 01:58:27,937
'We know where he was going.
Home, to the harvest.

928
01:58:32,982 --> 01:58:37,173
'Albert, of the class of 1916.

929
01:58:37,173 --> 01:58:41,489
'Out of the 20 who enlisted,
13 are dead.

930
01:58:41,613 --> 01:58:44,126
'Four are missing.

931
01:58:44,250 --> 01:58:47,607
'One is in a madhouse.

932
01:58:47,607 --> 01:58:51,683
'You and I live. How I miss you.'

933
01:58:52,305 --> 01:59:52,841
